In equity. The transformation of one species of property into another, as money into land or land into money; or, more particularly, a fiction of law, by which equity assumes that such a transformation has taken place (contrary to the fact) when it is rendered necessary by the equities of the case,—as to carry Into effect the directions of a will or settlement,—and by which the property so dealt with becomes invested with the properties and attributes of that Into which it is supposed to have been converted. Seymour v. Freer, 8 Wall. 214, 19 L. Ed. 306; HMaward v. Peavey, 128 IIL 430, 21 N. H 503, 15 Am. St. Rep. 120;

Yerkes vy. Yerkes, 200 Pa. 419, 50 Atl. 186; Appeal of Clarke, 70 Conn. 195, 39 'Atl. 156. At law. An unauthorized assumption and exercise of the right of ownership over goods or personal chattels belonging to another, to the alteration of their condition or the exclusion of the owner's rights. Baldwin v. Cole, 6 Mod. 212; Trust Co. v. Tod, 170 N. Y. 233, 68 N. E. 285; Boyce v. Brockway, 31 N. Y. 490; University v. Bank, 96 N.. G 280, 3 8. E. 359; Webber v. Davis, 44 Me. 147, 69 Am. Dec. 87; Gilman v. Hill, 36 N. H. 311; Stough v. Stefani, 19 Neb. 468, 27 N. W. 445; Schroeppel v. Corning, 5 Denio (N. ¥.) 286; Aschermann ¥. Brewing Co., 45

